Level-0 Motion: Should the Basics of Law Be Taught in High School? (As an Elective), Side: for
    Level-1 Your Main Claim: {"claim": "High schools should offer introductory law electives to better prepare students for potential legal careers.", "argument": ["Current exposure to law is inadequate for career preparation.", "If niche electives are offered, a foundational law course is justifiable."]}
        Level-2 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A basic understanding of the law should be mandatory in schools.", "argument": ["Informed citizenry is essential for a functioning democracy.", "The judiciary is a crucial part of the government."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "Basic legal literacy is crucial for responsible citizenship, supporting law as a required elective.", "argument": ["Basic legal literacy is important for responsible citizenship.", "Law can be a required elective, similar to physical education or health.", "These electives are outside the core curriculum."]}
                Level-4 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "Government and law are distinct subjects, both crucial for informed citizenship but covering different material.", "argument": ["Government focuses on the workings of the political system.", "Law examines legal processes and citizens' rights.", "Both are crucial for informed citizenship."]}
                Level-4 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A mandatory law class offers practical, real-world knowledge applicable throughout life, unlike redundant repetition of material.", "argument": ["Mandatory law class offers practical, real-world knowledge.", "Avoids redundant repetition of material."]}
                Level-4 Opponent's Attack: {"claim": "A law requirement could be flexible and integrated into the curriculum without disrupting existing academic pathways.", "argument": ["Law requirement can be flexible, similar to P.E. or health.", "Ensures legal knowledge reaches students without disrupting academic pathways."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "The structure of other courses sharing credit classifications does not dictate the structure of this proposal.", "argument": ["The fact that other courses share credit classifications does not mean this proposal must follow the same structure."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "The debate should focus on the specific proposal of a law elective, not broader educational philosophies.", "argument": ["Broader educational philosophies are acknowledged but are not the central point of the debate.", "The debate should concentrate on the merits of the specific law elective proposal."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "A basic law elective is more akin to health class \u2013 crucial knowledge, but not requiring four years of dedicated study.", "argument": ["Core classes imply yearly study.", "This proposal is more like health class, which is important but doesn't require four years of study."]}
            Level-3 Your Rebuttal: {"claim": "The proposal is more accurately classified as a required elective.", "argument": ["Based on the previous points, the proposal is best understood as a required elective."]}
